00:36:18,551 --> 00:36:21,137
when a group of
about 500 protestors

746
00:36:21,220 --> 00:36:22,763
blocked rush hour traffic.

747
00:36:22,847 --> 00:36:24,724
It was called a Day of Outrage--

748
00:36:24,807 --> 00:36:29,145
outrage which continued today
despite attempts by city leaders

749
00:36:29,228 --> 00:36:30,730
to put the best
face on the verdict.

750
00:36:30,813 --> 00:36:33,649
Mayor Koch says he's not
gonna give any special treatment

751
00:36:33,733 --> 00:36:36,319
to any of the people
arrested in the Day of Outrage.

752
00:36:36,402 --> 00:36:39,822
The Day of Outrage,
as they refer to it,

753
00:36:39,906 --> 00:36:41,949
took place before the verdict

754
00:36:42,033 --> 00:36:43,242
in the Howard Beach case.

755
00:36:43,326 --> 00:36:45,620
They were knocking
it, condemning it, before

756
00:36:45,703 --> 00:36:47,121
they knew what it was.

757
00:36:47,205 --> 00:36:49,832
Is that the way to get your way?

758
00:36:49,916 --> 00:36:52,585
To demonstrate and
to impose yourself?

759
00:36:52,668 --> 00:36:56,547
'Cause I don't think that's
what Blacks or whites want.

760
00:36:56,631 --> 00:36:58,216
[Reporter]: It would
be safe to say, though,

761
00:36:58,299 --> 00:36:59,675
that you're not hailing
last night's verdict

762
00:36:59,759 --> 00:37:01,135
as justice in New York City.

763
00:37:01,219 --> 00:37:02,428
We want to hold comment.

764
00:37:02,511 --> 00:37:04,722
We have to bury Yvonne Smallwood

765
00:37:04,805 --> 00:37:06,140
tomorrow night in the Bronx.

766
00:37:06,224 --> 00:37:08,726
28-year-old Black
mother of four children

767
00:37:08,809 --> 00:37:11,729
beaten to death by New York
City policemen in the Bronx.

768
00:37:11,812 --> 00:37:14,357
And so we're gonna have
this funeral tomorrow night.

769
00:37:14,440 --> 00:37:17,068
This struggle of racism and
racially motivated violence

770
00:37:17,151 --> 00:37:18,569
in New York City
is not over with.

771
00:37:18,653 --> 00:37:21,322
The Howard Beach verdict
does not end anything.

772
00:37:21,405 --> 00:37:24,408
[indistinct chatter]

773
00:37:28,454 --> 00:37:32,500
We have everything
in this movement.

774
00:37:34,877 --> 00:37:37,004
We have nationalists.

775
00:37:37,088 --> 00:37:39,173
We have revolutionaries.

776
00:37:39,257 --> 00:37:41,384
We have people who want
to overthrow the government.

777
00:37:41,467 --> 00:37:47,473
[shouting, cheering, applause]

778
00:37:48,266 --> 00:37:50,226
And the reason why
we will continue to have

779
00:37:50,309 --> 00:37:51,852
everything in this movement,

780
00:37:51,936 --> 00:37:53,229
because it frightens white folks

781
00:37:53,312 --> 00:37:56,816
when we have everything
in this movement.

782
00:37:56,899 --> 00:37:59,610
[cheers and applause]

783
00:37:59,694 --> 00:38:03,322
It lets white folks know that
we might be Malcolm today

784
00:38:03,406 --> 00:38:05,324
and Martin Luther King tomorrow.

785
00:38:05,408 --> 00:38:08,369
[cheering, shouting]

786
00:38:11,831 --> 00:38:13,874
[applause]

787
00:38:13,958 --> 00:38:16,460
Those that oppress us

788
00:38:16,544 --> 00:38:20,172
had the nerve to
try and advise us

789
00:38:20,256 --> 00:38:24,677
on how we ought to
try to get free from them.

790
00:38:24,760 --> 00:38:26,053
[laughing]

791
00:38:26,137 --> 00:38:31,684
[cheers and applause]

792
00:38:36,022 --> 00:38:39,859
[Sharpton]: We are
intelligent enough

793
00:38:39,942 --> 00:38:42,194
not to let you tell us

794
00:38:42,278 --> 00:38:47,408
what tactics that you
are comfortable with

795
00:38:47,491 --> 00:38:49,327
to hold us in slavery.

796
00:38:49,410 --> 00:38:52,371
[cheers and applause]

797
00:38:52,496 --> 00:38:55,374
[Sharpton]: You don't have
none of us under control.

798
00:38:55,458 --> 00:39:00,713
[cheers and applause]

799
00:39:02,840 --> 00:39:06,218
And you will never have
us under control again.

800
00:39:06,302 --> 00:39:10,389
[cheers and applause]

801
00:39:11,640 --> 00:39:14,101
[Sharpton]: That
was Howard Beach.

802
00:39:15,895 --> 00:39:18,272
It felt like a victory,

803
00:39:18,356 --> 00:39:21,776
but you knew that
you won a case,

804
00:39:21,859 --> 00:39:24,987
not changed the system.

805
00:39:25,196 --> 00:39:26,489
I'd been in the
movement since 12,

806
00:39:26,572 --> 00:39:30,951
and I knew the difference
between moments

807
00:39:31,035 --> 00:39:33,412
and movements that won.

808
00:39:33,496 --> 00:39:37,083
So it was a good
momentary victory.

809
00:39:37,166 --> 00:39:41,504
[cheers and applause]

810
00:39:41,754 --> 00:39:45,091
But I knew there was
no structural change

811
00:39:45,174 --> 00:39:47,635
in the criminal justice system.

812
00:39:48,260 --> 00:39:51,305
{\an8}If you had some
advice for young people,

813
00:39:51,389 --> 00:39:53,808
{\an8}what would you tell 'em?

814
00:39:53,891 --> 00:39:56,602
{\an8}Well, first thing I'd say,
get yourself together,

815
00:39:56,685 --> 00:39:59,563
because before you can
get anything else together,

816
00:39:59,647 --> 00:40:03,818
you gotta get me, I, yourself.

817
00:40:03,901 --> 00:40:06,654
Hey, that's very short,
but it's very direct.

818
00:40:06,737 --> 00:40:08,364
We have a young
man in the studio

819
00:40:08,447 --> 00:40:11,283
who I think is an
astounding young brother

820
00:40:11,367 --> 00:40:15,204
because of his youth,
he's only 19 years old,

821
00:40:15,287 --> 00:40:16,580
and he's accomplished a lot.

822
00:40:16,664 --> 00:40:20,000
And he's here to make a
presentation to James Brown.

823
00:40:20,084 --> 00:40:22,378
And we'd like to
welcome him warmly.

824
00:40:22,461 --> 00:40:25,881
His name is Al Sharpton.
How about it for Al Sharpton?

825
00:40:25,965 --> 00:40:29,135
[applause]

826
00:40:29,218 --> 00:40:33,055
Al is the national
director of...

827
00:40:33,139 --> 00:40:34,974
- The National--
- The National Youth--

828
00:40:35,057 --> 00:40:36,976
- Movement.
- Movement, Incorporated.

829
00:40:37,059 --> 00:40:38,352
- Right, Al?
- That's right.

830
00:40:38,436 --> 00:40:39,645
And what do we have here?

831
00:40:39,728 --> 00:40:43,274
Well, we come
to break tradition.

832
00:40:43,357 --> 00:40:45,443
We know that in the
recording industry

833
00:40:45,526 --> 00:40:46,735
that they give a gold record

834
00:40:46,819 --> 00:40:49,363
to those that achieve
a million seller.

835
00:40:49,447 --> 00:40:52,241
But we view your
million seller, Payback,

836
00:40:52,324 --> 00:40:55,244
as a Black record, because
it is relevant and says

837
00:40:55,327 --> 00:40:58,289
many of the things that
young Blacks have tried to say

838
00:40:58,372 --> 00:41:02,418
and could not musically
express in our own little way.

839
00:41:02,501 --> 00:41:05,963
And we feel The Payback is
sort of the like the theme song

840
00:41:06,046 --> 00:41:08,549
of young Black America in 1974.

841
00:41:08,632 --> 00:41:10,759
[cheers and applause]

842
00:41:10,926 --> 00:41:13,679
[Sharpton]: James
Brown was the biggest,

843
00:41:13,762 --> 00:41:18,893
most regarded, legendary
Black star in the world at that time.

844
00:41:18,976 --> 00:41:24,899
And this was at one of
the lowest points in my life.

845
00:41:25,274 --> 00:41:27,359
- Where were you born?
- Brooklyn, New York.

846
00:41:27,776 --> 00:41:29,320
[Charlie Rose]: Yeah,
your dad left you--

847
00:41:29,403 --> 00:41:30,488
When I was 10 years old.

848
00:41:30,571 --> 00:41:32,114
[Rose]: And how
does that shape you?

849
00:41:32,198 --> 00:41:33,657
How have you lived with that?

850
00:41:33,741 --> 00:41:35,659
Well, it is certainly something

851
00:41:35,743 --> 00:41:39,538
that makes you reach outside
of your home for male figures.

852
00:41:39,705 --> 00:41:42,291
[Sharpton] I woke up one
morning. My father had left.

853
00:41:42,374 --> 00:41:46,670
He had left with my
stepsister, and they had a child.

854
00:41:46,879 --> 00:41:51,383
It impacted me more than
I would admit to myself.

855
00:41:51,634 --> 00:41:54,053
When my daddy left,

856
00:41:54,136 --> 00:41:56,555
my mother became
mother and father.

857
00:41:56,639 --> 00:42:01,018
Sixty percent of young
African children grow up

858
00:42:01,101 --> 00:42:03,145
with just their momma at home.

859
00:42:03,229 --> 00:42:05,272
{\an8}Hello, Rev. This is your mother.

860
00:42:05,356 --> 00:42:08,192
{\an8}And I think so very much
every time I hear you speak,

861
00:42:08,275 --> 00:42:09,777
{\an8}every time I see you perform,

862
00:42:09,860 --> 00:42:11,904
{\an8}every time I see
your lovely work--

863
00:42:11,987 --> 00:42:15,324
I just think about how
good God has been to me

864
00:42:15,407 --> 00:42:17,910
now and through the
years that I delivered you

865
00:42:17,993 --> 00:42:19,578
for these, our people.

866
00:42:19,662 --> 00:42:24,542
[Sharpton]: I was
looking for a father figure.

867
00:42:24,625 --> 00:42:29,213
The wisdom of my
mother was she understood

868
00:42:29,630 --> 00:42:34,343
that if she didn't guide me
around the right male figures,

869
00:42:34,426 --> 00:42:37,930
that I was, because
of this hunger,

870
00:42:38,013 --> 00:42:42,518
would seek them out, and it
might be negative male figures.

871
00:42:42,601 --> 00:42:44,270
- Where did you grow up?
- [Sharpton]: In Brownsville,

872
00:42:44,353 --> 00:42:46,564
which is probably the
worst part in the city.

873
00:42:46,647 --> 00:42:50,317
Mike Tyson came out of there.
And you know, I'm 37 now.

874
00:42:50,401 --> 00:42:52,444
Most--I can't
think of two friends

875
00:42:52,528 --> 00:42:54,029
{\an8}that are not either
in jail or dead.

876
00:42:54,113 --> 00:42:57,449
{\an8}[Sharpton] So when she
brought me to Bishop Washington,

877
00:42:57,533 --> 00:43:00,119
{\an8}and he brought me
to a Reverend Jones

878
00:43:00,202 --> 00:43:01,412
{\an8}and a Jesse Jackson,

879
00:43:01,495 --> 00:43:04,748
{\an8}that was because she
was smart enough to say,

880
00:43:04,832 --> 00:43:06,834
{\an8}"He's gonna need
that in his life."

881
00:43:06,917 --> 00:43:11,589
My Father's Day is about those
that have fathered our community.

882
00:43:11,672 --> 00:43:12,506
[audience affirming]

883
00:43:12,590 --> 00:43:13,632
[Woman]: That's right!

884
00:43:13,716 --> 00:43:16,635
Those that pay the extra price.

885
00:43:16,719 --> 00:43:20,806
Those that have done
what needed to be done,

886
00:43:20,889 --> 00:43:24,685
even when others
were not willing to do it.

887
00:43:24,768 --> 00:43:27,271
I always gave her credit,

888
00:43:27,354 --> 00:43:33,360
that this uneducated
Black woman from Alabama,

889
00:43:33,444 --> 00:43:37,615
never studied child-rearing,
never studied psychology,

890
00:43:37,698 --> 00:43:39,575
but she knew that.

891
00:43:39,658 --> 00:43:42,578
We got too many
young people in America

892
00:43:42,661 --> 00:43:45,914
who do not have two
parents to look up to,

893
00:43:45,998 --> 00:43:47,541
and there's only so many hours--

894
00:43:47,625 --> 00:43:50,586
And that problem is
compounded by a young mother

895
00:43:50,669 --> 00:43:52,504
who is now being unemployed,

896
00:43:52,588 --> 00:43:54,882
whose job's been given
to international markets,

897
00:43:55,090 --> 00:43:56,383
who has no daycare help,

898
00:43:56,467 --> 00:43:58,469
who has no type of assistance

899
00:43:58,552 --> 00:43:59,720
from the federal government.

900
00:43:59,803 --> 00:44:01,305
So he has no role model.

901
00:44:01,388 --> 00:44:02,765
His mother can't
take care of him.

902
00:44:02,848 --> 00:44:05,517
He's thrown in the streets
with no educational program.

903
00:44:05,601 --> 00:44:08,854
He watches television that
gives him a digest of violence.

904
00:44:08,937 --> 00:44:11,774
And then he's incarcerated
when he takes TV's advice

905
00:44:11,857 --> 00:44:14,193
and picks up a gun and
plays Have Gun - Will Travel.

906
00:44:14,276 --> 00:44:17,446
Probably if he had not left
and they had stayed together,

907
00:44:17,529 --> 00:44:20,115
I would have been a
much different person,

908
00:44:20,324 --> 00:44:21,784
'cause I probably
would've never known

909
00:44:21,867 --> 00:44:23,118
the difference of zip codes.

910
00:44:23,202 --> 00:44:26,246
I would've never saw the
father figure in Adam Powell,

911
00:44:26,330 --> 00:44:29,333
or Jesse Jackson,
or James Brown.

912
00:44:29,416 --> 00:44:32,628
[chatter]

913
00:44:32,711 --> 00:44:36,507
[Sharpton]: And I understood
what a lot of people

914
00:44:36,590 --> 00:44:37,716
didn't get to understand.

915
00:44:37,800 --> 00:44:41,220
I knew both sides of
the Black experience.

916
00:44:41,303 --> 00:44:42,596
There's one thing about you is

917
00:44:42,680 --> 00:44:44,848
I know as long as you're
involved, I'm involved.

918
00:44:44,932 --> 00:44:46,392
I'm committed to
you 'cause I know

919
00:44:46,475 --> 00:44:47,976
you're trying to do something.
- Thank you, sir.

920
00:44:48,060 --> 00:44:48,811
I sure thank ya.

921
00:44:48,894 --> 00:44:50,562
[Sharpton]: I learned
from James Brown

922
00:44:50,646 --> 00:44:54,400
that if you really
find your rhythm

923
00:44:54,483 --> 00:44:58,195
and find what you
believe in and what you do,

924
00:44:58,278 --> 00:45:04,368
that sooner or later, the
world will cross over to you

925
00:45:04,451 --> 00:45:06,704
rather than you
cross over to them.

926
00:45:06,787 --> 00:45:09,748
[siren wailing]

927
00:45:25,264 --> 00:45:26,932
[phone ringing]

928
00:46:13,020 --> 00:46:19,109
[ mournful vocalizing ]

929
00:46:27,701 --> 00:46:29,495
People have called
for charges to be laid,

930
00:46:29,578 --> 00:46:31,955
but this crowd is
wondering what does it take?

931
00:46:32,039 --> 00:46:34,666
Back before there were video,
they could understand that.

932
00:46:34,750 --> 00:46:35,751
Now they can't.

933
00:46:35,834 --> 00:46:37,127
People are calling
it a lynching.

934
00:46:37,211 --> 00:46:39,046
[Anchor]: Frustration
over the lack of charges

935
00:46:39,129 --> 00:46:42,132
against the officers
turned into anger overnight,

936
00:46:42,216 --> 00:46:44,510
{\an8}and it all comes as Minnesota
and the rest of the country

937
00:46:44,593 --> 00:46:47,846
{\an8}are facing the dual toll
of rising jobless claims

938
00:46:47,930 --> 00:46:49,640
{\an8}and cases of coronavirus.

939
00:46:49,723 --> 00:46:52,643
{\an8}All you need is probable
cause to make an arrest.

940
00:46:52,726 --> 00:46:55,103
{\an8}And there is no reason
why these four policemen

941
00:46:55,187 --> 00:46:57,523
{\an8}should not have
been arrested by now.

942
00:46:57,606 --> 00:46:58,816
{\an8}[Female anchor]: Protests
breaking out in at least

943
00:46:58,899 --> 00:47:02,152
{\an8}140 cities across the country.

944
00:47:02,236 --> 00:47:07,199
{\an8}[Reporter]: The nation
erupted into scenes of chaos,

945
00:47:07,282 --> 00:47:07,991
{\an8}violence.

946
00:47:08,242 --> 00:47:10,577
{\an8}There are people here
who are really, really angry

947
00:47:10,661 --> 00:47:13,205
{\an8}about the systemic issues
that they're talking about.

948
00:47:13,288 --> 00:47:15,624
{\an8}As part of Minneapolis
burned last night,

949
00:47:15,707 --> 00:47:17,543
{\an8}one of President
Trump's tweets, quote,

950
00:47:17,668 --> 00:47:20,754
{\an8}"When the looting
starts, the shooting starts."

951
00:47:20,838 --> 00:47:23,423
{\an8}These criminal
acts are not protest.

952
00:47:23,507 --> 00:47:25,342
{\an8}They are not statements.

953
00:47:25,425 --> 00:47:27,427
{\an8}Does this violence help?

954
00:47:27,511 --> 00:47:28,679
{\an8}It doesn't help anything,

955
00:47:28,762 --> 00:47:30,681
{\an8}but it lets you know
that they're tired!

956
00:47:30,764 --> 00:47:33,475
{\an8}They're tired of being
oppressed, being misused,

957
00:47:33,559 --> 00:47:35,811
{\an8}being abused, being
murdered at will!

958
00:47:35,894 --> 00:47:38,146
{\an8}What do you mean by
"Justice should be served"?

959
00:47:38,230 --> 00:47:42,442
{\an8}I'll leave that to the
justice system to work out.

960
00:47:42,526 --> 00:47:44,987
{\an8}There's this tinge
a horrific irony,

961
00:47:45,070 --> 00:47:48,907
{\an8}to hear calls for
tranquility and status quo

962
00:47:48,991 --> 00:47:51,159
{\an8}when justice has still
not been delivered.

963
00:47:51,243 --> 00:47:53,996
I'm not gonna pretend
for a millisecond

964
00:47:54,079 --> 00:47:57,124
to know what it's like to be
a Black person in America.

965
00:47:57,207 --> 00:47:58,250
I don't.

966
00:47:58,333 --> 00:48:01,378
But the only thing I do know
is that we all need to do better.

967
00:48:01,461 --> 00:48:02,462
We need to love more.

968
00:48:02,546 --> 00:48:05,424
We need to respect
more. Do better.

969
00:48:05,507 --> 00:48:06,675
So part of what we have to do

970
00:48:06,758 --> 00:48:08,594
is try to understand
the context.

971
00:48:08,677 --> 00:48:10,137
[Tucker Carlson]:
Oh, the context.

972
00:48:10,220 --> 00:48:12,639
And squint your eyes as you
said. "The context." Of course!

973
00:48:12,723 --> 00:48:15,434
There's a context to
setting fire to McDonald's,

974
00:48:15,517 --> 00:48:16,727
says Professor Gloud.

975
00:48:16,810 --> 00:48:20,480
I think that this could
be a tipping point

976
00:48:20,564 --> 00:48:21,982
to have this conversation.

977
00:48:22,065 --> 00:48:24,109
But you cannot
have a conversation

978
00:48:24,192 --> 00:48:25,986
until these officers
are arrested

979
00:48:26,069 --> 00:48:28,739
{\an8}and show that we are
dealing on a playing field

980
00:48:28,822 --> 00:48:31,992
{\an8}that is even and that
is fair to everyone.

981
00:48:32,075 --> 00:48:34,828
{\an8}Without that, it's
talk with no action.

982
00:48:34,912 --> 00:48:36,371
We don't just need
a conversation.

983
00:48:36,455 --> 00:48:42,169
We need the implementation
and execution of the law.

984
00:48:42,961 --> 00:48:44,755
[Man] Solidarity and respect.

985
00:48:44,838 --> 00:48:47,132
{\an8}All right, thanks.

986
00:48:53,388 --> 00:48:55,807
{\an8}[Sharpton]: Tyler's
giving us the planes,

987
00:48:55,891 --> 00:49:00,103
{\an8}and Robert Smith is doing
